John Edward: Language skills are a necessity for global citizens
The private schools in Scotland are known for the outstanding performance of their students and it has continued in 2018 with new, impressive test results, which are still supported by individual and group results in sports, arts, music and other social disciplines.
These schools have up to 30,000 students all over Scotland, with the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) in charge of them, and they strive to provide their students and their parents with the best possible service.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for further postgraduate studies, the career they have chosen and their status as a global citizen.
As a teaching sector that can put together and teach by specially designed curricula, we see that new language continues to be a popular subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, that touches his mind.
If you speak to him in his native language, it touches his heart.”
This is an important reminder that we can’t just rely on English to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The test results this year show us that languages are at the top of the lists with the highest percentages of students achieving exams in private schools.
Sixty-eight per cent of students who studied a foreign language received a grade of A.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS schools, showed that 72 percent of students received a grade of A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who learned German, 69 percent of those who learned French, and 63 percent of those who learned Spanish also received an A grade.
This shows that private schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a necessary skill that children and young people will certainly need in the future.
At the moment, languages, as an elective subject, are placed in the same position as science-related study material (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of private schools and elsewhere.
An opinion poll conducted in 2014 by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that, for the reasons given by employers to be difficult to recruit, 17 percent were due to a lack of people with language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future jobs.
As more and more jobs require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career they choose, they will have a real advantage in the future if they learn a second language, which is a skill that will last a lifetime.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will provide a multilingual character with an automatic advantage over competitors.
According to a YouGov poll of over 4,000 adult Britons in 2013, 75 percent of them couldn’t speak a second language well enough to sustain a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-letter percentage, or 15 percent.
Therefore, it is important for children of today to invest immediately in language teaching.
Multilingualism, especially in emerging markets, will give children a better chance to find meaningful work.
In Scotland, the language they teach varies from school to school.
A certain number of schools will focus on more classic new languages, while others will teach languages that are thought to be most important for the UK as we look forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
No matter where your child’s interest lies, they will always be able to choose from languages in private schools with specially trained teachers.
Scottish private schools are committed to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future brings.
It cannot be denied that at this time, in a global business environment, languages continue to be essential for the future of the country, and that must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be seen as “international communication skills.”
Private schools will continue to offer choices, diversity and excellence to Scotland’s youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edwards is the President of the Scottish Private School Council.
