North Korea says unilateral disarmament 'impossible' without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the UN on Saturday that the continued trade ban only extends to their distrust of the United States and it was impossible for the country to dismantle its nuclear weapons unilaterally under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho said at the annual UN General Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant steps to show goodwill” over the past year, for example, by halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and promising to halt the development of nuclear weapons and technologies.
"However, we have not seen any similar reaction from the United States," he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, there is no certainty about the safety of our country, and under such circumstances, it is impossible for us to unilaterally dismantle our nuclear weapons first.”
While Ri has repeated familiar North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “staged” approach to nuclear disarmament in which North Korea would be rewarded for every step it took, his statement seemed specific in that he did not deny unilateral nuclear disarmament outright as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to Kim Jong Un’s and Donald Trump’s joint statement at the first meeting of acting US presidents and North Korean leaders, in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim pledged to work for the “nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula,” and Trump pledged to ensure North Korea’s security.
North Korea has sought a solution to formally end the Korean War in 1950-53, but the United States has said Pyongyang must abandon its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also resisted calls to relax a strict trade embargo against North Korea.
“The United States is demanding ‘nuclear disarmament first’ and increasing pressure by using a trade embargo to achieve it, and even protesting the declaration to end the war,” Ri said.
“There are only dreamers of people who know nothing about us to think that a commercial farm can get us down.
But the problem is that the continued commercial prayer increases our distrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for another meeting between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader spoke about at the UN earlier this week.
Speaking instead of three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months, the minister added: “If the party to this nuclear disarmament issue were South Korea instead of the United States, this would not be a stalemate in the Korean nuclear disarmament issue.”
Despite this, the tone of Ri’s speech last year was very different when he said at the United Nations General Assembly that it was inevitable to target missiles from North Korea to the US mainland after “devil president” Trump called Kim a “firefighter” in a suicide attack.
Last year, Trump threatened to “deplete” North Korea, but this year he praised Kim at the United Nations for his courage in taking steps towards disarmament, saying there was still a lot of work to be done and that a trade ban would have to continue until North Korea had destroyed all of its nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for this, saying, “If it takes two years, three years, or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
However, Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that “the Security Council’s trade ban must remain in place until a complete nuclear disarmament has taken place and it is confirmed.”
The Security Council agreed to increase trade ties with North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to block funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for another meeting.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying progress had been made, but only a few hours later North Korea condemned him for making “criminal demands.”
North Korea promised at a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear facility if the United States took “corresponding action.”
He said Kim had told him that the “corresponding actions” he sought were assurances of security promised by Trump in Singapore and actions toward normal relations with Washington.
Students at Harvard take classes in sufficient rest
A new course at Harvard University has given all students more sleep in an attempt to counteract the increasing tendency of students to stay awake and study all night with the help of caffeine tablets.
A study revealed that students at the world’s best universities often know little or nothing about the basics of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and an expert at Brigham and the Women’s Hospital, designed the course and believes it to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea to do the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning ability.
“At the end of the lecture, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I being told this first now, in my final year?’
She said that no one had told her anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told Telegraph.
The course, held for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help learning ability and performance in sports and even contribute to overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director of the School of Health Sciences, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students were very sleep-deprived over the week.
The course is an hour in length and includes various interactive assignments.
In one part there is a picture of a room in a dormitory, where students click on a cup of coffee, curtains, sports shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how performance in sports can worsen with lack of sleep, as well as the importance of a good routine for sleep.
In the second part, participants are told how lack of sleep over the long term can increase their risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Maps of the school campus with interactive icons then encourage participants to think about their daily habits.
“We know that this will not change the behaviour of the students at once.
But we think they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know about the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” Professor Czeisler added.
The culture that celebrates those who stay awake and study all night is still there, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Ensuring you get enough good quality sleep should be the “secret weapon” of students to combat stress, fatigue, and anxiety, he said — even to avoid fattening, because sleep deprivation heightens the brain’s call for food so that the body is alert.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student of chemistry and physics from California, helped Professor Czeisler put the course together, who sat one of the professor’s classes last year during his freshman year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and encouraged him to call for a course for all students in the school.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all Master’s students to complete a similar course before they start studying at the university.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm, which reminds them to go to sleep, and to wake them, keeping in mind the harmful effects of blue light emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can confuse the internal clock of the body and lead to trouble falling asleep.
