Almanac: The man who invented the Geiger counter
Here is a page from our calendar "Sunday Morning": September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today and today... this is the day that the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method to detect and measure radioactivity and that invention eventually led to a device called a Geiger meter.
The Geiger meter has gained a solid place in the scientific world since then, but was also popular in pop culture, for example in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", with Roy Rogers and Dale Evans in unlikely roles as scientists:
Man: “What the hell is this?”
Rogers: “This is a Geiger detector, used to find radioactive materials such as uranium.
When you put these headphones on, you can hear the effects of the atoms because of the radioactivity in the stones."
He said, “It’s really happening right now!”
“Hans” Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name lives on.
