What is the International Civil Festival and has it done anything to reduce poverty?
The Global Citizen Festival will be held on Saturday in New York. It is an annual music event where a series of big stars will emerge and with a similarly influential strategy; to end poverty around the world.
This is the seventh year that the International Civil Festival is being held and tens of thousands of people will flock to Central Park, not only to listen to music acts from Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to highlight the festival’s real goal of ending extreme poverty by 2030.
The International Civil Festival, first held in 2012, is part of the Global Poverty Project, an international campaign to end poverty by increasing the number of people fighting it.
To get free tickets to the event (except for those who want to pay for VIP tickets), concertgoers had to complete various tasks, or “actions,” such as volunteering, sending an email to one of the world’s leaders, making a phone call, or using other valid means to help draw attention to their goal of ending poverty.
But how successful has the festival been, already 12 years in the making?
Is the idea of rewarding people with free gigs really a way to convince people to call for action, or is this just one so-called “click action” – where people feel they are doing something that matters by signing online petitions or sending a message on Twitter?
Global Citizen says that since 2011, it has recorded over 19 million “actions” from its supporters, to call for a variety of different goals.
It says these actions have helped get world leaders to declare commitments and policies equivalent to over $35 billion that will impact the lives of over 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group counted 390 commitments and announcements for its actions, of which at least USD 10 billion have been invested or raised.
The group estimates that the funds raised so far have directly affected nearly 649 million people worldwide.
One of the main commitments comes from The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based investor and executive that works to “help children enjoy themselves to the fullest,” and pledged to provide $35 million to Rwanda to help end malnutrition in the country, after receiving 4,700 messages on Twitter from Global Citizens.
“With the support of the UK government, donors, governments around the world and international citizens like you, we can make the social injustice of malnutrition a thing of the past,” said Tracey Ullmann, representative of The Power of Nutrition at a concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that after 5,000 petitions were sent for Britain to improve nutrition for mothers and children, the government announced a funding project, the Power of Nutrition, which will reach 5 million women and children and provide them with better nutrition.
In the list of frequently asked questions on the group’s website, one question is: “Why do you think you can end extreme poverty?”
Global citizen replied: “It will be a long and difficult task – sometimes we will fail all the time.
But, we will reach our goal, just like the movements that fought for the rights of citizens and the abolition of racial segregation before us, because we are stronger together.
