Syria 'ready' for refugees to return, says foreign minister
Syria says it is ready for refugees to return to the country and is seeking help to rebuild the country, which is now in a bad state after a seven-year war.
Foreign Minister Walid al Moualem, speaking at the UN General Assembly, said the situation in the country was improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure, thanks to the success of the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to restore normal conditions by building up areas that were completely destroyed by terrorists.
All is now ready for refugees to return willingly to the country they were forced to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic decisions that targeted their daily lives and jobs.
More than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war began in 2011.
An additional six million people still living in the country are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian government would be happy to help rebuild the country.
However, he stressed that they would not accept conditional aid or aid from countries that supported the uprising.
Europe wins Ryder Cup in Paris
Europe has won the 2018 Ryder Cup by beating the United States with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 points at Le Golf National, outside Paris, France.
The U.S. has lost six times in a row on European grounds and has not won the Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained its crown when the team, led by Danish captain Thomas Bjorn, achieved the 14.5 points it needed to defeat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who struggled the most during the entire race, made his debut into the water on the 16th hole, a par 3, losing his game to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari shone brightly in all of his matches, becoming 1 of 4 players to get a 5-0-0 score, since the competition started using its current format in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth lost 5&4 against Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark, but he was in the bottom position in the ranking of the players in the European team.
Dustin Johnson, who is in the top spot on the list of the world's best golfers, lost 2 and 1 to Ian Poulter of England who played possibly in his last Ryder Cup competition.
Spanish Sergio Garcia, who has played eight times for the Ryder Cup, became the most successful European player with 25.5 career points.
“I usually don’t cry, but today I can’t do anything else.
This has been a difficult year.
I am so grateful to Thomas for choosing me and believing in me.
I am so happy to have the cup back.
It's about the team, and it was my pleasure to be able to help," Garcia said after the European win.
He handed his country the John Rahm torch, defeating US golf legend Tiger Woods 2&1 in a solo match on Sunday.
“I was incredibly proud to have beaten Tiger Woods. I grew up watching him,” said 23-year-old Rahm.
Woods lost all four of his games in France and is now listed as 13-21-3 in the Ryder Cup.
This is a strange result for one of the best players in history, who has won 14 major titles and is only in second place behind Jack Nicklaus.
The U.S. team struggled all weekend to find themselves on the pitch, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who played a good game throughout the race.
U.S. captain Jim Furyk said of his team’s performance, “I’m proud of them, they fought.
It was in the early hours of the morning that we pushed Europe.
We lost him down.
I'll take over for Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All 12 players played very well.
We’ll get back together, I’ll be working with the PGA of America and the Ryder Cup and we’ll keep going.
I love these 12 men and am proud to be their captain.
You have to take it from above.
They played better than us.”
Latest news of algae blooms: Density decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest news from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in the concentration of algae blooms in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more brittle algal blooms are reported in certain areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota Charlotte and Collier counties – suggesting declining concentrations.
The algal bloom extends for about 200 miles [40 km] of coastline from northern Pinellas to southern Lee counties.
You can find unique blooms about 10 miles (16 km) from Hillsborough County, but in fewer places compared to last week.
Algal blooms have also been reported in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or near Pinellas County were reported last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, very low to high concentrations in Manatee County, very low to high concentrations in or near the coast of Sarasota County, very low to moderate concentrations in Leeborough County, and very low to high concentrations in Charlotte County.
Respiratory tract irritation is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory tract irritation was reported in northwestern Florida over the past week.
